1. The Problem: "Color" and Self-Interaction
Unlike photons, which are electrically neutral and don't interact with each other, gluons (the carriers of the strong force) carry "color charge." This means gluons interact with themselves.

    Standard QCD: This self-interaction causes "Asymptotic Freedom" (the force gets weaker as quarks get closer) and "Confinement" (the force gets stronger as they pull apart).
    The Math Problem: Because gluons are self-referential, the math of QCD is notoriously difficult to solve—we often rely on "Lattice QCD" (massive computer simulations) because we lack a clean analytical solution.

